{{Infobox academic | honorific_prefix = <!-- see [[MOS:HONOURIFIC]] --> | name = Horacio Roque Ramírez | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames --> | birth_date = {{birth date|1969|11|15}} | birth_place = [[Santa Ana, El Salvador]] | death_date = {{death date and age|2015|12|25|1969|11|15}} | death_place = [[Los Angeles, California]] | death_cause = | region = | nationality = [[Salvadoran Americans|Salvadoran American]] | citizenship = | residence = | other_names = | occupation = | period = | known_for = | title = | boards = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation--> | spouse = | children = | parents = | relatives = | awards = <!--notable national level awards only--> | website = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of California, Berkeley]] | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | school_tradition = | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | influences = <!--must be referenced from a third party source--> | era = | discipline = [[Chicana/o studies]] | sub_discipline = [[Oral history]], [[LGBT history]] | workplaces = [[University of California, Santa Barbara]] | doctoral_students = <!--only those with WP articles--> | notable_students = <!--only those with WP articles--> | main_interests = | notable_works = | notable_ideas = | influenced = <!--must be referenced from a third party source--> | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | footnotes = }}
'''Horacio N. Roque Ramírez''' (November 15, 1969 – December 25, 2015)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ebar.com/obituaries/index.php?sec=ob&article=1023|title=The Bay Area Reporter Online - Horacio N. Roque Ramírez|website=Ebar.com|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> was a [[Salvadoran Americans|Salvadoran American]] [[oral history|oral historian]], writer and advocate whose work focused on [[LGBT community|LGBT]] [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]] communities and the Central American experience in the [[United States]]. He was a faculty member in the Department of [[Chicana/o studies|Chicana and Chicano Studies]] at the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicst.ucsb.edu/news/announcement/268|title=Professor Horacio Roque Ramírez - Department of Chicana and Chicano Studies - UC Santa Barbara|website=Chicst.ucsb.edu|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref>
==Early life== Roque Ramírez was born in [[Santa Ana, El Salvador]]. Fleeing the [[Salvadoran Civil War]], he immigrated to [[Los Angeles]] at age 12, in 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailynexus.com/2016-01-08/vigil-held-to-honor-professors-otis-madison-and-horacio-roque-ramirez/|title=Vigil Held To Honor Professors Otis Madison and Horacio Roque-Ramirez|website=Dailynexus.com|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> He earned a B.A. in [[psychology]] and M.A. in [[history]] at [[UCLA]], and a Ph.D. in [[Ethnic Studies]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref name="oralhistory.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.oralhistory.org/2016/02/01/oha-remembers-horacio-roque-ramirez/|title=OHA Remembers Horacio Roque Ramirez|website=Oralhistory.org|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> He [[came out]] as a gay man in 1992.<ref name="sjsu.edu">{{cite journal|url=http://www.sjsu.edu/people/julia.curry/courses/MAS275/s2/Roque-Ramirez-My-Community.pdf |format=PDF |title=My Community, My History, My Practice |author=Horacio N. Roque Ramírez |journal=The Oral History Review|volume=29|date=2002 |pages=87-91 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]}}</ref>
==Research== Roque Ramírez began his [[oral history]] work with [[San Francisco]]'s queer Latina/o community, centered in the [[Mission District]], as a doctoral student at [[UC Berkeley]] in the 1990s,<ref name="sjsu.edu"/> working with activists and organizations including [[Diane Felix]] and [[Proyecto ContraSIDA por Vida]], and documenting predecessor organizations such as the Gay Latino Alliance.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.sjsu.edu/people/julia.curry/courses/MAS275/s2/Roque-Ramirez-Thats-My-Place.pdf |format=PDF |title="That's My Place!": Negotiating Racial, Sexual, and Gender Politics in San Francisco's Gay Latino Alliance, 1975-1983 |author=Horacio N. Roque Ramírez |journal=Journal of the History of Sexuality |volume=12 |date=April 2003 |pages=224-258 |publisher=[[University of Texas Press]]}}</ref>
At the time of his death he was working on the book ''Queer Latino San Francisco: An Oral History, 1960s-1990s''. He also served as an expert witness on political asylum and immigration.<ref name="oralhistory.org"/>
==Publications== * Alamilla Boyd, Nan, and Horacio N. Roque Ramírez. ''Bodies of Evidence: The Practice of Queer Oral History''. New York, NY: [[Oxford University Press]], 2012.
