{{BLP primary sources|date=September 2009}} {{Infobox philosopher | honorific_prefix = | name = Wiebe E. Bijker | honorific_suffix = | image = Bijker.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | other_names = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1951|03|19}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | death_cause = | residence = | nationality = [[Netherlands|Dutch]] | religion = | alma_mater = [[University of Twente]] | notable_works = <!-- use "notable_works" in place of "books" parameter (deprecated) --> | awards = | signature = | signature_size = | signature_alt = | era = | region = | school_tradition = | institutions = | main_interests = | notable_ideas = [[Social Construction of Technology|Social Construction of Technology-approach]] | influences = | influenced = [[Sally Wyatt]] | website = https://www.maastrichtuniversity.nl/w.bijker }}
'''Wiebe E. Bijker''' (born 19 March 1951, [[Delft]]) is a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] professor Emeritus, former chair of the Department of Social Science and Technology at [[Maastricht University]] in the [[Netherlands]].
== Early life == Bijker's father was an engineer involved in implementing the [[Delta Works|Delta Plan]] after a disastrous [[dike breach]] in the Netherlands in 1953 when young Bijker was two years old and later became deputy director of the Delft Hydraulics Laboratory.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Bijker | first1 = Wiebe E. | title = The Oosterschelde storm surge barrier: a test case for Dutch water technology, management, and politics | journal = [[Technology and Culture]] special issue, Water Technology in the Netherlands | volume = 43 | issue = 3 | pages = 569–584 | publisher = The Johns Hopkins University Press via JSTOR | date = July 2002 | jstor = 25147960 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref> Presumably, the unique fact of parts of the Netherlands being below sea level, the well-known concerns in innovation surrounding this condition for centuries, and his father's involvement all contributed to the younger Bijker's interest in technology studies.<ref>See also {{citation | last = Latour | first = Bruno | author-link = Bruno Latour | contribution = Centres of calculation | editor-last = Latour | editor-first = Bruno | editor-link = Bruno Latour | title = [[Science in Action (book)|Science in action: how to follow scientists and engineers through society]] | publisher = Harvard University Press | location = Cambridge, Massachusetts | year = 1987 | page = 230 | isbn = 9780674792913 }} ''et seq.'' Latour, a colleague of the younger Bijker, uses the father's genius in engineering to illustrate how scientists gain control over, or mobilize, difficult-to-manage objects.</ref>
== Education == After finishing [[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]] in [[Emmeloord]] (1969), the younger Bijker received his [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] degree in philosophy from the [[University of Amsterdam]] (1974), his [[engineer's degree]] in physical engineering from the [[Delft University of Technology]] (1976), and his [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] degree from the [[University of Twente]] in 1990.
== Career == Bijker was an [[assistant professor|assistant]] and [[associate professor]] of philosophy from 1987 at the [[Maastricht University]] before becoming [[full professor]] of technology and society in 1994. Bijker's fields of research include social and historical studies of [[science, technology and society]]; theories of technology development; methodology of science, technology and society studies; democratisation of technological culture; science and technology policies; ICT, multimedia and the social-cultural dimensions of the information society; gender and technology; and meta studies of architecture, planning, and civil engineering. With [[Trevor Pinch]] he is considered as one of the main adherents of the [[Social Construction of Technology]]-approach.<ref>{{citation | last = Tympas | first = Aristotle | contribution = Methods in the history of technology, Volume 2 M-Z Index | editor-last1 = Hempstead | editor-first1 = Colin | editor-last2 = Worthington | editor-first2 = William E. | title = Encyclopedia of 20th-century technology | publisher = Routledge | location = New York, New York | year = 2005 | page = 487 | isbn = 9781579583866 }}</ref> However, Bijker received criticism regarding his Dutch MFS-II-evaluation of 8,000 pages where he used a one-sided methodology of research with peer reviews.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160315040700/http://www.nl-aid.org/large-scale-mfs-ii-evaluation-conducted-by-wiebe-bijker-claims-without-evidence Large-scale MFS II-evaluation conducted by Wiebe Bijker claims without evidence]</ref>
On 12 May 2017 Wiebe Bijker became emeritus professor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maastrichtuniversity.nl/w.bijker|title=Wiebe Bijker (W.E.) - Maastricht University|website=www.maastrichtuniversity.nl|language=en|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref>
